Introduction ¶

Phase 1 Summary¶

The purpose of our Phase 1 report was twofold - a) to clean the data and prepare it for modeling b) data visualization. Our dataset did not have any irrelevant features to drop. We renamed the columns 'x', 'y','z' and 'depth' to length, width, depth and depth percentage respectively for better readability. Next, we checked the dataset for missing values and found none. After that, we noticed that the dataset had some observations where the measurements were 0, which is physically impossible. So we proceeded to remove those observations. At this point, we considered the data clean.

The Phase 1 report used several types of graphs to visualize the data, such as scatter-plots, box diagrams and bar graphs. We saw that the color 'G' seems to be the most popular among diamonds sold. Carat and price have an exponential relationship and diamonds with SI2 clarity generally have higher prices compared to diamonds with other types of clarity. Overall, carat seems to be the most significant feature in determining the price of the diamond. Premium SI2 diamonds seem to be the most expensive type. Moreover, Ideal cut diamonds have a higher demand according to our observations. We also noticed during our data visualization that the observations for our target feature 'price' are right skewed.

The cleaned dataset from Phase 1 will be used for modeling in Phase 2 of the project. The data visualization section provided insight into which variables must be transformed for modeling.

Report Overview¶

The goal of the Phase 2 report is to investigate whether we can come up with a reliable model for predicting diamond prices using the "diamonds" dataset. In this report, we will fit our dataset into a regression model and carry out multiple linear regression. We will perform dummy encoding on the categorical variables to fit them into the model. Once the model has been fitted, we verify whether the model fulfills the four conditions required for regression. Next, we carry out backward feature selection to remove any feature that is not statistically significant and then check the diagnostics of the reduced model. At the end, we analyze our model and find its limitations to figure out whether the model is appropriate to predict the price of a diamond.

Overview of Methodology¶

For our project, we are using the method Multiple Linear Regression to model our data. Linear regression is one of the most commonly used methods for supervised machine learning when the dependent variable is numeric. Multiple linear regression is a statistical technique that uses several explanatory variables to predict the outcome of a response variable. It is an extension of ordinary least squares regression (OLS) because it involves more than one explanatory variable. (Hayes, 2021) Mathematically, it can be expressed as: $$ \hat{\text{y}} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_1 + \beta_2 x_2 + ... + \beta_k x_k $$
where,
$\hat{\text{y}}$ is the predicted value of the response variable y
$\beta_0 $ is the intercept
$ \beta_k $ is the slope
$k $ is the number of explanatory variables, and
$ x $ is the explanatory variable.

The feature we will be predicting in our report is the price of a diamond.

In order to perform regression on our dataset, we make the assumptions that our data meets the following conditions:

  1. The relationship between each explanatory variable and the response variable is linear.
  2. The residuals have a nearly normal distribution.
  3. The observations in our dataset are independent of each other.
  4. The variability of points around the least squares line is roughly constant.

After modeling our data, we will check whether our dataset meets these conditions.

To analyze our model, we will use the adjusted $R^2$ value. R is the correlation coefficient of the explanatory variables and the response variable. $R^2$ tells us what percent of variability in the response variable is explained by the model. We use the adjusted $R^2$ value, which is a ratio of explained and unexplained variability, because it can provide a more precise view of the correlation by also taking into account how many independent variables are added to a particular model. A proper model is expected to have an R-squared value of over 70%.

Statistical Modelling ¶

Model Overview¶

The dataset being used in this report is the "diamonds" dataset sourced from the ggplot2 R library. This dataset contains information about the prices of diamonds. The features in our dataset are described in the table below.

Name Data Type Units Description
carat Numeric Carat Weight of the diamond
cut Ordinal categorical NA Quality of the cut
color Ordinal categorical NA Color of the diamond
clarity Ordinal categorical NA Measurement of how clear the diamond is
depth Numeric NA Total depth percentage
table Numeric NA Percentage for width of top of diamond relative to widest point
x Numeric mm Length of diamond
y Numeric mm Width of diamond
z Numeric mm Depth of diamond
price Numeric US $ Price of diamond

We are going to use multiple linear regression on the dataset to predict an estimate of our response variable, price. Firstly, we perform one-hot-encoding (OHE) on the categorical variables. This is required as the Statsmodels module cannot do automatic variable selection on categorical variables. Then we use python to create a string for constructing the regression formula. Next, we fit an OLS (ordinary least squares) model to our encoded data. We analyze the p-values of the data and perform backward feature selection to remove statistically insignificant features. We then carry out diagnostic checks on both the full model and the reduced model to see whether they fulfill the regression assumptions. As mentioned above, we use the adjusted $ R^2$ value to analyze the effectiveness of the model.

We will now check the diagnostics for the full model.

Full Model Diagnostic Checks¶

We would like to check whether there are indications of violations of the regression assumptions, which are

  1. linearity of the relationship between target variable and the independent variables
  2. constant variance of the errors
  3. normality of the residual distribution
  4. statistical independence of the residuals

Let's first get a scatter plot of residuals (as a function of predicted price).

In [9]:
plt.scatter(residuals_full['predicted'], residuals_full['residual'], alpha=0.3);
plt.xlabel('ln_Predicted_Price');
plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.title('Figure 2(a): Scatterplot of residuals vs. log of predicted price for Full Model', fontsize=15)
plt.show();

From Figure 2(a), we see that the residuals are mostly random and centered around 0, although not completely. There are few outliers which has very low predicted price but the value of residuals is quite high. Our graph is quite consistent for higher ln_predicted_price. This pattern indicates that the constant variability assumption of linear regression is mostly satisfied in this case.

Let's now plot actual price vs. residuals.

We noticed from Figure 4(a) that the histogram is right skewed due to the presence of outliers. Hence, it seems that the normality assumption of linear regression is violated in this particular case.

Now we check whether the residuals have a normal distribution if we remove the outliers of the residuals.

In [13]:
q1 = residuals_full['residual'].quantile(0.25)
q3 = residuals_full['residual'].quantile(0.75)

IQR = q3-q1
lower = q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper = q3 + 1.5 * IQR

for res in residuals_full['residual']:
    if (res < lower) | (res > upper):
        residuals_full['residual'] = residuals_full[['residual']].replace(res,np.NaN)
        residuals_full.dropna(inplace=True)
In [14]:
plt.hist(residuals_full['residual'], bins = 10);
plt.xlabel('Residual');
plt.ylabel('Frequency');
plt.title('Figure 4(b): Histogram of residuals for Full Model after removing outliers', fontsize=15);
plt.show();

From Figure 4(b), we see that the histogram is symmetric and centered at 0. This tells us that if we remove the outliers from the residuals, the model fulfills the normality assumption of linear regression.

Feature Selection¶

In the summary table of our full model above, we can see that the P > |t| column does not have any value that is greater than 0.05. So we can conclude that all our features are statistically significant. Hence, we do not have to carry out backward selection to remove insignificant features. Since we do not have any features to remove, we won't have a reduced model.

Critique & Limitations ¶

One of the most noticeable strengths of our model is that it does not have any statistically insignificant features. All of the features have strong correlation with the target variable 'price' as all of the p-values are around 0.00. Figure 1 showed us that most of the data is closely clustered around the regression line so the residuals are extremely low. The graphs also suggest that the data is mostly consistent. Moreover, the multiple linear regression model has an Adjusted R-squared value of about 97% which is commendable and makes the model highly reliable.

The prominent flaw in our model are the outliers present in the data. With outliers present in the data, the normality assumption of linear regression is violated. This suggests that our model cannot accurately predict extreme values, such as diamonds that are extremely expensive or diamonds that have very low prices. If we were to include the outliers in the data, it might be the case that nonlinear models such as a neural network might be more appropriate for the task at hand rather than a linear regression model.

Summary & Conclusions ¶

Project Summary¶

In Phase 1 of the project, we took on the tasks of data cleaning, preprocessing and data visualization. We checked whether all the columns were relevant to our goal, which they were. We renamed some of the columns as mentioned in the introduction. Then we checked whether the data types of the variables matched the intended data types. The dataset did not have any errors in this regard. After that, we checked the unique values for the categorical variables to ensure they did not have variations of the same value. Next, we noticed from the summary table of the numerical values that the minimum length, width and depth were 0. These values are invalid so we cleaned the dataset by removing those observations. We chose not to remove the outliers from the features as the values fall within a valid range. Afterwards, we plotted some graphs to visualize the data and better understand the relationships between the variables.

Data visualization in Phase 1 told us that the target variable 'price' was skewed. In Phase 2 of the project, we started with the cleaned dataset and performed log transformation on 'price' for better modeling. We also performed one-hot-encoding on the categorical variables. Then we created the regression formula of the encoded data and fit it into an OLS model. After fitting the model, we looked at its summary to find the variability explained by our model. We also checked the p-values to ensure all the features were statistically significant. Since all the p-values were below 0.05, we did not have to carry out feature selection to remove insignificant features. Furthermore, we conducted diagnostic checks to verify whether our model fulfills the conditions of linear regression. We analyzed the results of these checks to identify the strengths and weaknesses of our model.

Summary of Findings¶

Our model has an adjusted R-squared value of 0.97. In Figure 2(a) and 2(b), we can see that the residuals are mostly centered around 0 and have very low values. The summary of the model showed that the p-values of all the features are around 0.00, which means that all the features are statistically significant. The main obstacle in our model are the outliers. All the graphs plotted follow a proper pattern but have outliers. In Figure 5(b), we see that once the outliers are removed, the residuals become normally distributed and have a smaller range of around $ \pm 0.4. $

Conclusions¶

Since our adjusted R-squared value is above 90%, we can conclude that our model is a very good predictor of the price of a diamond. All of our features are highly relevant. Due to the high explained variability of the model, it can be used in the real-world by diamond retailers. Potential customers can use the model individually to figure out the ideal cut, clarity, and size of a diamond within their budget. In conclusion, the model can be considered valid and useful.
